		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">(i)  We wish to now exploit the element specificity of SPAES (and possibly SPXPS) to look at induced magnetism at interfaces between magnetic and  nearly magnetic  layers.  As a reference, we want first to look at SPAES and SPXPS in Pd:Fe thick films grown on ferromagnetic glass substrates.  We shall then move to systems of high current interest such the Gd:W multilayers in which anomalously high moments have been observed.  We shall obtain samples initially from Dr Donovan at Birkbeck.  (ii) We shall investigate fully the anisotropy switching we have seen in our preliminary data on the Fe:Si(lll) system, using in-situ SMOKE and low resolution SEMPA.  We are most interested in the correlation between the microstructure of the films and the magnetism.  (iii)  We aim to develop a spin rotator, based on a Wien filter, which will fit into the transfer optics of both our instruments.  This will allow us to measure all three polarisation components with the same efficiency and will be of particular value to future studies of the element-specific surface anisotropy.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
